answerText: Andrew Marvell[10] The second stanza of "To His Coy Mistress" concludes with a quip that this entity is "a fine and private place, but none I think do there embrace."

subject: Literature
question: Question: This poet described how the title object "congealed on earth; but does, dissolving, run into the glories of the almighty sun" in his "On a Drop of Dew." For 10 points each: [10] Name this 17th-century English poet of "The Garden" and "To His Coy Mistress."
